Core Definitions
# Origin: 
This is the default name Git gives to the repository you cloned. If you forked a project, origin points to your copy of the code on the server where you have "push" access.
# Upstream:
 This is a conventional name for the original repository you forked from. It is used to "fetch" the latest changes from the official project to keep your local work in sync.

 Fork a project on GitHub to create your own copy.Clone your fork locally: git clone <your-fork-url>. This automatically sets your fork as origin.Add Upstream to stay updated with the original project:git remote add upstream <original-repo-url>Sync your local code by fetching from the official source:git fetch upstreamPush your work to your own fork:git push origin feature-branch



